User:Generate the lists of enumerations, classes and attributes from a given <Description>.
#Description 
The CelO application helps families and groups of friends to organize birthday celebrations and other events. Organizers can keep track of which tasks have been completed and who attends. Attendees can indicate what they are bringing to the event.

For a small event, there is typically one organizer, but larger events require several organizers. An organizer provides their first and last name, their email address (which is also used as their username), their postal address, their phone number, and their password. Furthermore, an organizer indicates the kind of event that needs to be planned by selecting from a list of events (e.g., birthday party, graduation party or creating a new kind of event. The start date/time and end date/time of the event must be specified as well as the occasion and location of the event. The location can again be selected from a list, or a new one can be created by specifying the name of the location and its address. An organizer then invites the attendees by entering their first and last names as well as their email addresses. Sometimes, an organizer is only managing the event but not attending the event. Sometimes, an organizer also attends the event. When an attendee receives the email invitation, the attendee can create an account (if they do not yet have an account) with a new password and their email address from the invitation as their username. Afterwards, the attendee can indicate whether they will attend the event, maybe will attend the event, or cannot attend the event. An organizer can view the invitation status of an event, e.g., how many attendees have replied or have not yet replied and who is coming for sure or maybe will be coming.

When an organizer selects an event, an event-specific checklist is presented to the organizer. For example, a birthday party may have a task to bring a birthday cake. For each task on the checklist, an organizer can indicate that the task needs to be done, has been done, or is not applicable for the event. An organizer can also add new tasks to the list, which will then also be available for the next event. For example, an organizer can add to bring birthday candles to the list for a birthday party and this task will then be available for the next birthday party, too. An organizer can also designate a task on the checklist for attendees to accomplish. For example, an organizer can indicate that the birthday cake should be brought to the event by an attendee. If this is the case, then the list of tasks to be accomplished by attendees is shown to attendees that have confirmed their attendance to the event. An attendee can then select their tasks, so that the organizer can see who is bringing what to the event.

AI:### Enumerations:
1. EventTypes {BirthdayParty, GraduationParty, CustomEvent}
2. AttendeeResponse {Attending, MaybeAttending, NotAttending}
3. TaskStatus {ToDo, Done, NotApplicable}

### Classes:
1. Organizer
   - Attributes:
     - firstName: String
     - lastName: String
     - email: String
     - postalAddress: String
     - phoneNumber: String
     - password: String
     - eventTypes: List<EventTypes>

2. Event
   - Attributes:
     - startDate: DateTime
     - endDate: DateTime
     - occasion: String
     - location: Location

3. Location
   - Attributes:
     - name: String
     - address: String

4. Attendee
   - Attributes:
     - firstName: String
     - lastName: String
     - email: String
     - password: String
     - attendeeResponse: AttendeeResponse
     - tasks: List<Task>

5. Task
   - Attributes:
     - description: String
     - status: TaskStatus
     - assignedTo: Attendee

### Notes:
- The Organizer class represents the person organizing the event.
- The Event class represents a specific event with its details like start and end date, occasion, and location.
- The Location class represents the venue where the event will take place.
- The Attendee class represents a person who is invited to the event and can respond with their attendance status.
- The Task class represents a specific task that needs to be done for the event, with its description, status, and the attendee it is assigned to.

AI:Enumerations:
1. EventTypes {BirthdayParty, GraduationParty, CustomEvent}: Represents the different types of events that can be organized.
2. AttendeeResponse {Attending, MaybeAttending, NotAttending}: Represents the possible responses from attendees regarding their attendance status.
3. TaskStatus {ToDo, Done, NotApplicable}: Represents the status of a task on the checklist.

Classes:
1. Organizer(firstName: String, lastName: String, email: String, postalAddress: String, phoneNumber: String, password: String, eventTypes: List<EventTypes>): Represents the person organizing the event with their details and event preferences.
2. Event(startDate: DateTime, endDate: DateTime, occasion: String, location: Location): Represents a specific event with its details like date, occasion, and location.
3. Location(name: String, address: String): Represents a location where the event can take place.
4. Attendee(firstName: String, lastName: String, email: String, password: String, attendeeResponse: AttendeeResponse, tasks: List<Task>): Represents an attendee with their details and assigned tasks.
5. Task(description: String, status: TaskStatus, assignedTo: Attendee): Represents a specific task with its description, status, and the attendee it is assigned to.

AI:### Enumerations:
1. EventTypes (Birthday Party, Graduation Party, Custom): Represents different types of events that can be organized. 
2. InvitationStatus (Replied, Not Replied, Confirmed, Maybe, Not Attending): Defines the status of event invitations for attendees.
3. TaskStatus (To Do, Done, Not Applicable): Indicates the status of tasks in the event checklist.

### Classes:
1. Organizer(firstName: String, lastName: String, email: String, postalAddress: String, phoneNumber: String, password: String, eventTypes: List<EventTypes>, events: List<Event>): Represents the organizer of events with their personal information and organized events.
2. Event(startDate: Date/Time, endDate: Date/Time, occasion: String, location: Location, attendees: List<Attendee>, tasks: List<Task>): Represents an event with its details, attendees, and checklist of tasks.
3. Location(name: String, address: String): Represents the location where the event will be held.
4. Attendee(firstName: String, lastName: String, email: String, password: String, eventInvitations: List<EventInvitation>, tasks: List<Task>): Represents an attendee with personal information, event invitations, and assigned tasks.
5. EventInvitation(event: Event, attendee: Attendee, invitationStatus: InvitationStatus): Represents the invitation of an attendee to an event with the invitation status.
6. Task(description: String, status: TaskStatus, assignedTo: Attendee): Represents a task in the event checklist with its description, status, and assignment to an attendee.

#Description 
The CelO application helps families and groups of friends to organize birthday celebrations and other events. Organizers can keep track of which tasks have been completed and who attends. Attendees can indicate what they are bringing to the event.

For a small event, there is typically one organizer, but larger events require several organizers. An organizer provides their first and last name, their email address (which is also used as their username), their postal address, their phone number, and their password. Furthermore, an organizer indicates the kind of event that needs to be planned by selecting from a list of events (e.g., birthday party, graduation party or creating a new kind of event. The start date/time and end date/time of the event must be specified as well as the occasion and location of the event. The location can again be selected from a list, or a new one can be created by specifying the name of the location and its address. An organizer then invites the attendees by entering their first and last names as well as their email addresses. Sometimes, an organizer is only managing the event but not attending the event. Sometimes, an organizer also attends the event. When an attendee receives the email invitation, the attendee can create an account (if they do not yet have an account) with a new password and their email address from the invitation as their username. Afterwards, the attendee can indicate whether they will attend the event, maybe will attend the event, or cannot attend the event. An organizer can view the invitation status of an event, e.g., how many attendees have replied or have not yet replied and who is coming for sure or maybe will be coming.

When an organizer selects an event, an event-specific checklist is presented to the organizer. For example, a birthday party may have a task to bring a birthday cake. For each task on the checklist, an organizer can indicate that the task needs to be done, has been done, or is not applicable for the event. An organizer can also add new tasks to the list, which will then also be available for the next event. For example, an organizer can add to bring birthday candles to the list for a birthday party and this task will then be available for the next birthday party, too. An organizer can also designate a task on the checklist for attendees to accomplish. For example, an organizer can indicate that the birthday cake should be brought to the event by an attendee. If this is the case, then the list of tasks to be accomplished by attendees is shown to attendees that have confirmed their attendance to the event. An attendee can then select their tasks, so that the organizer can see who is bringing what to the event.
